      "rationale": "Three-mesh Richardson extrapolation performed; GCI for pressure rise QoI = 2.1%. GCI for hemolysis index QoI = 8.4%, exceeding the 5% threshold due to high gradients in the impeller gap region. Refinement ratio r = 1.25 slightly below the required 1.3. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments conducted with blood analog and porcine blood at VAD operating conditions; temperature, hematocrit, and flow waveform controlled and documented to within ±5% of COU targets.",
      "rationale": "Experiments used porcine blood at 37°C ± 0.5°C and hematocrit 33% ± 2%. Flow waveforms were steady-state approximations; pulsatile VAD operation not replicated in bench tests. Temperature and hematocrit within tolerance but waveform mismatch introduces systematic bias. Achieved level 3 vs. required 5."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation metric (E%) < 15% for hemolysis index across all five operating points with statistical comparison accounting for experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Hemolysis index errors range 8.7–12.3% across four of five operating points, within the 15% threshold. At the 4.5 L/min, 3300 RPM operating point, error = 18.1%, exceeding the threshold. Statistical comparison uses simple percent error without formal hypothesis testing. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation QoIs directly map to COU QoIs (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH); no surrogate quantities used.",
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is NIH, directly relevant to COU. Velocity profiles and pressure rise used as secondary validation QoIs to build confidence in flow field fidelity. The hemolysis model was calibrated on a different pump geometry (axial flow pump), introducing model form uncertainty not fully characterized. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
